  "text": "# Controller Registration with Manager in Kubernetes\n\nIn kubernetes/kubernetes, controllers register themselves with the controller manager through a descriptor-based initialization pattern rather than the `SetupWithManager` pattern used in controller-runtime.\n\n## Core Components\n\n### 1. **ControllerDescriptor** (controllermanager.go:421-429)\nDescribes a controller with metadata including:\n- `name`: Controller identifier\n- `initFunc`: Function that initializes and starts the controller\n- `aliases`: Backward-compatible names\n- `requiredFeatureGates`: Feature gates needed\n- `isDisabledByDefault`: Whether the controller is disabled by default\n- `isCloudProviderController`: Whether this is a cloud provider-specific controller\n\n### 2. **InitFunc Type** (controllermanager.go:419)\n```go\ntype InitFunc func(ctx context.Context, controllerContext ControllerContext, controllerName string) (controller controller.Interface, enabled bool, err error)\n```\nThe InitFunc is the equivalent of `SetupWithManager` - it's responsible for:\n- Creating the controller instance\n- Configuring event handlers and informers\n- Starting the controller's reconciliation loop\n- Returning whether the controller was enabled and any errors\n\n### 3. **ControllerContext** (controllermanager.go:366-401)\nProvides controllers with necessary resources:\n- `ClientBuilder`: For creating API clients\n- `InformerFactory`: For creating informers to watch Kubernetes resources\n- `ObjectOrMetadataInformerFactory`: For watching typed and dynamic resources\n- `ComponentConfig`: Controller-specific configuration\n- `RESTMapper`: For mapping resources to REST endpoints\n- `InformersStarted`: Channel signaling when informers have started\n- `ResyncPeriod`: Function generating periodic resync intervals\n- `ControllerManagerMetrics`: For tracking controller metrics\n- `GraphBuilder`: For garbage collector dependency tracking\n\n### 4. **controller.Interface** (staging/src/k8s.io/controller-manager/controller/interfaces.go:25-55)\nThe base interface that all controllers must implement:\n- `Name() string`: Returns the controller's canonical name\n- Optional `Debuggable` interface: Provides debugging HTTP handlers\n- Optional `HealthCheckable` interface: Provides health check endpoints\n\n## Controller Registration Flow\n\n### Step 1: Descriptor Definition\nEach controller is defined through a `newXxxControllerDescriptor()` function. For example, in core.go:\n```go\nfunc newEndpointsControllerDescriptor() *ControllerDescriptor {\n    return &ControllerDescriptor{\n        name:     names.EndpointsController,\n        aliases:  []string{\"endpoint\"},\n        initFunc: startEndpointsController,\n    }\n}\n```\n\n### Step 2: Controller Initialization\nThe `initFunc` (e.g., `startEndpointsController`) is called to initialize the controller:\n```go\nfunc startEndpointsController(ctx context.Context, controllerContext ControllerContext, controllerName string) (controller.Interface, bool, error) {\n    go endpointcontroller.NewEndpointController(\n        ctx,\n        controllerContext.InformerFactory.Core().V1().Pods(),\n        controllerContext.InformerFactory.Core().V1().Services(),\n        controllerContext.InformerFactory.Core().V1().Endpoints(),\n        controllerContext.ClientBuilder.ClientOrDie(\"endpoint-controller\"),\n        controllerContext.ComponentConfig.EndpointController.EndpointUpdatesBatchPeriod.Duration,\n    ).Run(ctx, int(controllerContext.ComponentConfig.EndpointController.ConcurrentEndpointSyncs))\n    return nil, true, nil\n}\n```\n\n### Step 3: Manager Registration\nControllers are registered in `NewControllerDescriptors()` (controllermanager.go:495-593):\n```go\nregister(newEndpointsControllerDescriptor())\nregister(newEndpointSliceControllerDescriptor())\n// ... more controller registrations\n```\n\n### Step 4: Starting Controllers\nThe `StartControllers()` function (controllermanager.go:662-706) iterates through registered controllers and calls `StartController()` for each.\n\n`StartController()` (controllermanager.go:708-767):\n- Checks if controller is enabled\n- Calls the controller's `InitFunc`\n- Registers health checkers\n- Mounts any debugging handlers\n\n## Reconciliation Pattern\n\nKubernetes controllers use the **Reconciler** pattern internally for state reconciliation. Examples include:\n\n### Volume Manager Reconciler (pkg/kubelet/volumemanager/reconciler/reconciler_common.go:49-51)\n```go\ntype Reconciler interface {\n    Starts running the reconciliation loop which executes periodically, checks\n    if volumes that should be mounted are mounted and volumes that should\n    not be mounted are unmounted.\n    Run(stopCh <-chan struct{})\n}\n```\n\n### Plugin Manager Reconciler (pkg/kubelet/pluginmanager/reconciler/reconciler.go:37-41)\n```go\ntype Reconciler interface {\n    Run starts running the reconciliation loop which executes periodically,\n    checks if plugins are correctly registered or unregistered.\n    Run(stopCh <-chan struct{})\n}\n```\n\n### Attach/Detach Controller Reconciler (pkg/controller/volume/attachdetach/attach_detach_controller.go:301-305)\nThe attach/detach controller uses a reconciler to periodically reconcile the desired and actual state of volume attachments:\n```go\nreconciler reconciler.Reconciler\n```\n\n## Key Differences from controller-runtime\n\nWhile the Kubernetes native controllers don't use the `SetupWithManager` pattern from controller-runtime, they achieve the same goals through:\n\n1. **ControllerDescriptor** instead of SetupWithManager: Encapsulates controller metadata and initialization logic\n2. **InitFunc** instead of imperative setup: Declarative function that returns the initialized controller\n3. **ControllerContext** instead of Manager: Provides all necessary dependencies and resources\n4. **controller.Interface** instead of reconciler.Reconciler: Base interface for all controller types\n5. **Explicit Manager Loop**: The `Run()` function in controllermanager.go orchestrates controller startup and lifecycle\n\nThis design allows Kubernetes to manage many heterogeneous controllers with different initialization patterns and dependencies while maintaining a consistent registration and lifecycle management system."
